The formula for the Laplacian matrix L is\begin{align*}
L = D^{T} R^{-1} D
\end{align*}

But we can simply calculate the Laplacian matrix by computing the
following:

For the diagonal entries
($L_{ii}$)\begin{align*}
L_{ii} = \sum_{connected \ edges, i} \gamma_{i}
\end{align*}

For the non-diagonal edges
($L_{ij}$)\begin{align*}
L_{ij} = \sum_{shared \ edges j} \gamma_{j}
\end{align*} if there are
shared edges and $L_{ij} = 0$ if no shared edges

$\gamma = \frac{1}{R}$ Where R is the resistance of the edge. which in
this question $R = 1$ so $\gamma = 1$.

Following the equations given above, the Laplacian matrix
is\begin{align*}
L = \begin{bmatrix}
4 & -1 & -1 & -1 & -1 & 0\\ 
-1 & 4 & -1 & 0 & -1 & -1\\ 
-1 & -1 & 4 & -1 & 0 & -1\\ 
-1& 0 & -1 & 4 & -1 & -1\\ 
-1& -1 & 0 & -1 & 4 & -1\\ 
0 & -1 & -1 & -1 & -1 & 4
\end{bmatrix}
\end{align*}

The columns of matrix L are labeled as node 1 to 6 from left to right.

FINAL ANSWER

$L = \begin{bmatrix}
4 & -1 & -1 & -1 & -1 & 0\\ 
-1 & 4 & -1 & 0 & -1 & -1\\ 
-1 & -1 & 4 & -1 & 0 & -1\\ 
-1& 0 & -1 & 4 & -1 & -1\\ 
-1& -1 & 0 & -1 & 4 & -1\\ 
0 & -1 & -1 & -1 & -1 & 4
\end{bmatrix}$
